So I would just ask the Governor to stop commenting on stuff that he doesn't know about and we

00:06:55.000 --> 00:07:00.000
would respectfully say wait for the evidence to determine what she did or did not do.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:06.000
Griggs said he'll ask a judge to dismiss charges against Representative Cannon but committed

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:12.000
to take this all the way to a jury trial if necessary.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:17.000
A wave of bills that would restrict voting has flooded the nation.

00:07:17.000 --> 00:07:23.000
Last week Georgia became the eye of the storm with the passing of a bill that would restrict

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:27.000
voting and influence all parts of the election process.

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:30.000
Amara Evering has more.

00:07:30.000 --> 00:07:35.000
Last week Georgia Governor Brian Kemp signed a bill that would influence virtually all parts

00:07:35.000 --> 00:07:41.000
of the voting process behind the closed doors of his office under a scenic painting of

00:07:41.000 --> 00:07:45.000
a plantation hanging above his head on his wall.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:50.000
Kemp signed a bill that will essentially suppress votes in his own state.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:55.000
This bill will enact new limitations on absentee voting, criminalized passing out food and

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:00.000
drinks to voters waiting in long lines, and short and runoff periods.

00:08:00.000 --> 00:08:06.000
These are only a few of the restrictions on this bill and just outside Kemp's door was

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:12.000
Representative Park Cannon, a black woman who had been literally locked out of this process

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:16.000
and later arrested for simply knocking on his door.

00:08:16.000 --> 00:08:22.000
For many this was a symbolic moment from the scenic painting of a Georgia plantation hanging

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:27.000
above Kemp's head to the arrest of a black legislator outside his door.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:33.000
It was symbolic of systems of white supremacy being upheld as black voters and other voters

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:37.000
of color are being locked out of elections.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:43.000
I spoke to Anadena's, the executive director of Common Cause Georgia of voting rights organization

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:44.000
in the state.

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:49.000
For her these bills in Georgia reflect a legacy of racial oppression.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:57.000
These bills are reminiscent of everything that Georgians and people of color from brown

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:03.000
black indigenous that we have experienced since really reconstruction.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:09.000
These bills are slated to roll us back and they're using language that tries to make it

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:12.000
seem like this is a bipartisan bill.

00:09:12.000 --> 00:09:13.000
It is not.

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:17.000
This bill is definitely reminiscent of Jim Crow.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:23.000
We don't have to count bubbles in a lie bar of soap or count jelly beans in a jar.

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:30.000
Now we're having the stripped away like line warming where you can't give someone a

00:09:30.000 --> 00:09:33.000
punch or a bottle of water.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:40.000
This ban online warming disproportionately influences voters in urban areas and black voters whose

00:09:40.000 --> 00:09:46.000
precincts often have very long waits to cast ballots often spanning for hours.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:49.000
But the restrictions certainly don't stop there.

00:09:49.000 --> 00:09:55.000
They also influence mail-in voting and absentee voting by adding stricter ID requirements

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:59.000
and limiting the time frame that you could even request these ballots.

00:09:59.000 --> 00:10:03.000
People have a problem with our vote by mail system and Republicans have been using vote

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:06.000
by mail for 15 years.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:11.000
And this was a policy that was enacted by a Republican governor, sunny Purdue, and a

00:10:11.000 --> 00:10:13.000
Republican legislature.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:16.000
And there was no problems to it.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:20.000
And now all of a sudden there have been problems to it because there are so many people who

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:25.000
are now using this same system to come out to vote.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:32.000
Though Governor Kemp voted for absentee in mail-in voting in 2005 when it was a Republican-led

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:36.000
effort, 16 years later he's saying that it should be restricted.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:38.000
So what changed?

00:10:38.000 --> 00:10:44.000
Well up into the last couple of years, the relatively few people who used mail-in voting skewed

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:49.000
older, wider, and more Republican in Georgia.

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:56.000
But in 2020 what went from just a few mail-in voters turned into a fourth of voters in Georgia

00:10:56.000 --> 00:10:57.000
voting by mail.

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:02.000
And this time those voters were a little more diverse demographically.

00:11:02.000 --> 00:11:10.000
So what we say this is, this is very reactionary to the upheaval of people who actually exercised

00:11:10.000 --> 00:11:11.000
their voice.

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:13.000
And now people have a problem with it.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:17.000
But these bills aren't just a reaction to more people voting by mail.

00:11:17.000 --> 00:11:22.000
It's also a reaction to the massive voter turnout of the last election.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:27.000
There were so many people who had enthusiasm and was so excited about this election that

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:33.000
they sitting those eight hour lines that they came back and forth during early voting to

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:38.000
make sure that they can have their ballot and their voices heard.

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:47.000
And now we have Republicans, must be clear, it's Republicans who are saying that one, that

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:53.000
your voices it matter, this is what racism with the ballot box and oppression with the

00:11:53.000 --> 00:11:57.000
ballot box and suppression of the ballot box looks like.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:12:01.000
More legislators in Georgia that support this bill, they say that these restrictions are

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:04.000
necessary to combat voter fraud.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:07.000
But many are asking what voter fraud?

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:13.000
They're saying that there was voter fraud, there was voter security measures that weren't

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:14.000
taken.

00:12:14.000 --> 00:12:21.000
Here in Georgia we had an election that has been audited three times.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:24.000
So they're saying that there was fraud that took place.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:29.000
We know that there's no fraud that took place and there was no tampering of our elections.

00:12:29.000 --> 00:12:35.000
Our Georgia Bureau of Investigation, they investigate our elections and they found nothing.

00:12:35.000 --> 00:12:41.000
So maybe it wasn't that the votes were illegitimate, but that they were cast by the wrong people,

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:46.000
people that didn't skew older, wider and Republican for Anandennis.

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:49.000
She believes that these restrictions only really taken to account.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:53.000
The privileged and wealthy who live in Georgia.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:59.000
I firmly believe that they are trying to make elections for the privilege.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:06.000
The people who have means, who have security with transportation to be able to bounce around

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:08.000
to here and there to find an early voting precinct.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:12.000
But then there's a lot of people in Georgia who don't have that.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:17.000
But the bill that was passed last week is one of many bills that have been proposed in

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:19.000
Georgia to restrict voting.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:24.000
So there are over 60 bills that were proposed in our legislature.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:29.000
The impact of these bills will be dire to Georgia.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:33.000
It will restrict our secretary of state and our local board of elections.

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:40.000
It will create new rules on provisional validating down to changing provisions around people

00:13:40.000 --> 00:13:43.000
being able to use mobile precincts.

00:13:43.000 --> 00:13:48.000
These bills, including the bill that was just passed, will especially influence places in

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:51.000
Georgia like Fulton County.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:56.000
Fulton County is a majority black area where residents are more likely to use things like

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:02.000
drop boxes in mobile voting units and Anandennis believes that if all of these restrictions

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:09.000
resigned into law last year, our 2020 election may have looked very different.

00:14:09.000 --> 00:14:16.000
At this bill was signed in a law a year ago, we definitely would have had over 4.7 million

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:24.000
people who went out and voted either early vote or via vote by mail.

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:31.000
We would have had people being able to use like drop boxes.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:36.000
Just the numbers of people being registered wouldn't have happened.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:42.000
People who stood in line for, you know, six to eight hours to cast their ballot during

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:46.000
the early vote timeframe, they probably would have went home.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:52.000
And this means that moving forward, elections in Georgia will likely be different.

00:14:52.000 --> 00:14:55.000
The elections will look significantly different.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:15:03.000
It may look very similar to what we saw during post reconstruction and what we saw during

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:04.000
Jim Crow.

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:09.000
You will probably see a lot of people saying, I shouldn't have to feel like I'm doing a poll

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:11.000
text to vote.

00:15:11.000 --> 00:15:16.000
But the danger of this bill isn't just in the way it will affect Georgia.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:20.000
The danger is also in the way that it has already affected other states.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:26.000
What we're seeing is that this bill, these bills are copycatting across the country.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:34.000
They're copycatting in Minnesota, Pennsylvania, West Conson, Florida, Arizona.

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:38.000
They are copycatting these bills and other places as well.

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:44.000
According to the Brennan Center for Justice, as of last month, 250 bills that would restrict

00:15:44.000 --> 00:15:48.000
voting had been proposed in 43 states.

00:15:48.000 --> 00:15:53.000
Many of these bills focus on limiting mail-in voting and imposing stricter ID requirements

00:15:53.000 --> 00:15:58.000
on a Dennis believes that this signifies a turning point in our country.

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:01.000
This is a very powerful moment in our country.

00:16:01.000 --> 00:16:07.000
And I do feel like that right now that especially in Georgia, we are in a cultural shift and

00:16:07.000 --> 00:16:09.000
we're in a political cultural shift.

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:14.000
And Georgia is still trying to figure out where do we fall in line?

00:16:14.000 --> 00:16:16.000
The type of state will we be.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:19.000
So I think in our next election cycle, which is going to be our gubernatorial race, which

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:26.000
is a statewide race, we will see where Georgia falls and we will see the real impact of

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:28.000
these types of laws.

00:16:28.000 --> 00:16:33.000
Despite these bills, unindentists encourages us to still come out and vote.

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:40.000
But I'm hoping that we see that energy of if they're going to make it this hard for

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:41.000
me to vote.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:46.000
That means I'm going to stand in line and I'm going to keep staying in line for that

00:16:46.000 --> 00:16:50.000
six to eight hours just because they don't want me to have this right.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:57.000
And I'm going to make sure that my entire neighborhood knows about the regulations and

00:16:57.000 --> 00:17:04.000
the rules about requesting your mail-in ballot or going to, you know, your voting site.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:07.000
So I'm hoping that that energy will remain.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:12.000
That was Anadenas, Executive Director of Common Cause, Georgia.

00:17:12.000 --> 00:17:19.000
For more information and how to get involved, please visit common cause dot org slash Georgia.

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:23.000
And remember, your vote still matters.

00:17:23.000 --> 00:17:25.000
Don't let some little legislation scare you.

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:28.000
