00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:55.000
Last Wednesday, Governor Ralph Norbham signed a landmark bill banning the death penalty.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:18:00.000
The new law makes Virginia the 23rd state and the first of the old Confederate states

00:18:00.000 --> 00:18:04.000
to ban the death penalty completely.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:11.000
Since its first execution in 1608, Virginia has executed close to 1400 people more than

00:18:11.000 --> 00:18:15.000
any other state in the union.

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:20.000
In today's times, Virginia is second only to Texas and the number of people executed.

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:25.000
So why such a historic shift and why now?

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:27.000
So good when reports.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:33.000
Virginia's anti death penalty activists have been fighting for an end to capital punishment

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:34.000
for decades.

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:40.000
So news of last week's bill signing is surely seen as a moment of celebration, but also some

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:43.000
surprise that it happened as soon as it did.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:50.000
Michael Stone is the executive director of Virginians for alternatives to the death penalty,

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:57.000
an organization that first formed 30 years ago to advocate foreign end to state sponsored

00:18:57.000 --> 00:18:59.000
killing in Virginia.

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:04.000
He describes the moment he first realized that it was actually going to happen.

00:19:04.000 --> 00:19:10.000
That was back in January when the news broke that Governor Norbham would use an upcoming

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:35.000
address to call for abolition.

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:54.000
Michael Stone says he didn't expect this moment to actually happen for three to five years,

00:19:54.000 --> 00:20:00.000
but that endorsement from Norbham back in January was enough to push it over the top and

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:05.000
get the bill passed through both legislative chambers and onto the governor's desk for

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:06.000
a signature.

00:20:06.000 --> 00:20:11.000
But it was far from the only factor that moved this movement to a victory.

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:15.000
Stone says the work of the faith community is long been at the center of the death penalty

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:18.000
abolition movement in Virginia.

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:24.000
An important shift he says is that in recent years, a number of unexpected allies have joined

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:30.000
the movement, including the attorneys who are elected to prosecute crimes on behalf

00:20:30.000 --> 00:20:31.000
of the state.

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:38.000
In Virginia, we elect our prosecutors by locality and they're called Commonwealth attorneys.

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:47.000
And in the election of 2017 and 2019, many old time pro death penalty Commonwealth attorneys

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:49.000
were defeated or retired.

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:56.000
And in their stead were a group of younger, more progressive prosecutors who ran on

00:20:56.000 --> 00:21:02.000
platforms of either promising never to seek the death penalty or if they would only do

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:05.000
it rarely instead of a matter of course.

00:21:05.000 --> 00:21:12.000
And so we had 12 Commonwealth attorneys signed an open letter to the General Assembly

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:15.000
calling for our death penalty abolition.

00:21:15.000 --> 00:21:20.000
And together they represented nearly half the population of the Commonwealth of Virginia.

00:21:20.000 --> 00:21:26.000
Another essential element of this movement, Michael Stone says, are the voices of victims

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:32.000
families, people who are victimized themselves by a violent crime, but do not want to see

00:21:32.000 --> 00:21:37.000
the death penalty pursued in the deaths of their loved ones.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:43.000
We had a group of 21 victim family members write an open letter to the General Assembly

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:49.000
calling on them to end the death penalty saying that capital punishment did not help them,

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:53.000
but in fact harmed victim family members.

00:21:53.000 --> 00:21:59.000
And one of the most powerful spokespeople in testimony was Rachel Sutphen, the daughter

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:06.000
of Montgomery County Sheriff's Deputy Corporal Sutphen who was killed by Will Morva and

00:22:06.000 --> 00:22:11.000
Rachel made a private and public plea to then Governor McCall of to spare Morva's life

00:22:11.000 --> 00:22:14.000
because of a severe mental illness and delusions.

00:22:14.000 --> 00:22:21.000
But the governor never responded to Rachel and he allowed the execution to go on.

00:22:21.000 --> 00:22:27.000
Making Will Morva the last person executed in Virginia.

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:32.000
Yet another shift in Virginia's abolition movement that Michael Stone says has been

00:22:32.000 --> 00:22:38.000
absolutely critical is the deepening recognition that the death penalty is an issue of racial

00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:43.000
justice, one that reaches deep into American history.

00:22:43.000 --> 00:22:51.000
The death penalty and racial oppression have been tied together since the earliest days

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:52.000
of the republic.

00:22:52.000 --> 00:23:00.000
Death has always been a tool of racial terror and racial control, whether it be through

00:23:00.000 --> 00:23:05.000
official state sanctioned killing or through lynching.

00:23:05.000 --> 00:23:14.000
And the research clearly shows an overwhelming racial bias in application of the death penalty

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:16.000
throughout our history.

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:22.000
In fact, in 1848 that racial bias was actually codified into law.

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:31.000
In 1848, the Virginia General Assembly passed a law that black people could be executed

00:23:31.000 --> 00:23:39.000
for any crime for which a white person would receive a sentence of three years or more.

00:23:39.000 --> 00:23:46.000
So even the code made explicit the racial bias in application of the death penalty.

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:51.000
Data from the death penalty information center offers a picture of the impact of that

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:52.000
law.

00:23:52.000 --> 00:24:01.000
From 1900 until 1977, Virginia executed 73 black men on charges of rape, attempted rape

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:08.000
or robbery, while no white defendants were executed for these same crimes.

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:16.000
But even after the 1848 law was declared unconstitutional, racial discrimination in the application

00:24:16.000 --> 00:24:19.000
of the death penalty in Virginia persisted.

00:24:19.000 --> 00:24:23.000
So Virginia is about 20% African American.

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:32.000
Black inmates have accounted for 46% of the 114 people who have been executed statewide

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:34.000
since 1976.

00:24:34.000 --> 00:24:40.000
And it's not just the race of the perpetrator that perpetuated this bias.

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:45.000
Since 1976, the primary distinction is race of victim.

00:24:45.000 --> 00:24:50.000
In Virginia, for example, defendants were three times more likely to be sentenced to

00:24:50.000 --> 00:24:56.000
death in cases where the victim was white than if the victim was any other race.

00:24:56.000 --> 00:25:02.000
Now death penalty opponents have long pointed to capital punishments racial bias as the

00:25:02.000 --> 00:25:03.000
reason to abolish it.

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:09.000
But Michael Stone says two things happen that finally pushed Virginia in that direction.

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:16.000
Stone was the scandal over a racist photo of Governor Northam in a 1984 yearbook that

00:25:16.000 --> 00:25:19.000
sparked calls for him to resign.

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:25.000
Stone believes that outcry forced Northam to be more sensitive to racial justice.

00:25:25.000 --> 00:25:32.000
But it wasn't until the police murder of George Floyd and the ensuing public outrage over

00:25:32.000 --> 00:25:38.000
massive racial disparities in our criminal justice system that the movement to repeal the

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:42.000
death penalty in Virginia truly gained traction.

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:49.000
Legislators who had expressed support for death penalty abolition before then, they were

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:51.000
kind of lukewarm about it.

00:25:51.000 --> 00:25:57.000
Yeah, we'll get around to it, but it was not a pressing priority by any means, even among

00:25:57.000 --> 00:25:58.000
Democrats.

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:06.000
But all criminal justice reform issues were elevated dramatically after the emergence of an incredibly

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:11.000
strong Black Lives Matter movement in the wake of the George Floyd murder and the police

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:16.000
murders of other on-arm Black people.

00:26:16.000 --> 00:26:17.000
So what's next?

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:23.000
Speaking to the Washington Post last week, Michael Stone made this statement, quote, one

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:29.000
lesson we learned from other states is that the most dangerous time is the first year or

00:26:29.000 --> 00:26:32.000
two after a victory, unquote.

00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:35.000
And here's what he meant by that.

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:39.000
That is when the victory is most vulnerable to being reversed.

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:46.000
For example, in Nebraska, a Republican legislature voted to abolish the death penalty.

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:52.000
The Republican governor vetoed it and then that same Republican legislature overrode that

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:53.000
veto.

00:26:53.000 --> 00:26:57.000
But in that state, referendum or allowed under state constitution.

00:26:57.000 --> 00:27:03.000
So the governor immediately poured a few million dollars into a referendum campaign to

00:27:03.000 --> 00:27:10.000
get the question on the ballot and the voters reversed the decision of the legislature there

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:14.000
so that death penalty abolition never took effect.

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:19.000
Stone says it's important to make sure the same thing doesn't happen in Virginia where

00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:26.000
Republicans remain largely unified in opposition to death penalty abolition.

00:27:26.000 --> 00:27:32.000
And where in 2022, the state will elect a new governor and every 100 members of the House

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:35.000
of delegates is up for reelection.

00:27:35.000 --> 00:27:42.000
So in nine months, it's possible that we will have a pro-death penalty governor and a house

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:45.000
speaker who was pro-death penalty.

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:51.000
And with a narrow margin in the Senate, I would not be surprised if that happens that

00:27:51.000 --> 00:27:55.000
there will be an effort to reinstate the death penalty in Virginia next year.

00:27:55.000 --> 00:27:58.000
So what does that mean for Michael Stone's organization, for

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:02.000
Virginians, for alternatives to the death penalty?

00:28:02.000 --> 00:28:07.000
They could decide to close their doors given how hard it is to raise money for an organization

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:14.000
whose mission has been accomplished, or they could stay open to defend the victory and

00:28:14.000 --> 00:28:19.000
even broaden their mission to work on other criminal justice issues.

00:28:19.000 --> 00:28:23.000
So our board is going to be making that decision in about a month from now.

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:29.000
But even if we decide to close our doors, the ACLU of Virginia, the Virginia Catholic Conference

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:34.000
and the Virginia Interfaith Center for Public Policy will certainly work to defend that victory.

00:28:34.000 --> 00:28:39.000
Because they have all been key allies of ours through the years in the abolition fight.

00:28:39.000 --> 00:28:45.000
Michael Stone, executive director of Virginians, for alternatives to the death penalty.

00:28:45.000 --> 00:28:48.000
For Monday morning QB, I'm Sue Goodwin.

00:28:54.000 --> 00:29:03.000
Vertalot of talk recently about hate crimes.

00:29:03.000 --> 00:29:08.000
Well, if hate is a crime, it's certainly nothing new in the United States.

00:29:08.000 --> 00:29:11.000
It's been around since before the beginning of the country.

00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:18.000
That's why a major civil rights organization like the Leadership Conference on Civil Rights

00:29:18.000 --> 00:29:21.000
has a division fighting hate and bias.

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:25.000
Beckiman Roe is the director.

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:27.000
So he's always put it to that danger.

00:29:27.000 --> 00:29:29.000
We have had the information about it.

00:29:29.000 --> 00:29:31.000
The people of Georgia look the other way.

00:29:31.000 --> 00:29:34.000
So that's part of why we have this component.

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:40.000
Why we recognize that we're in the middle and be able to combat those if we fight together.

00:29:41.000 --> 00:29:47.000
Colleagues of mine often refer to the period that we're in now as the third reconstruction.

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:52.000
The first being anti-bellum, second being the civil rights movement.

00:29:52.000 --> 00:30:00.000
And now each of which was followed by a backlash, often a violent backlash,

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:10.000
is that what's the hate violence that we see now, an inevitable result of the progress that was

00:30:10.000 --> 00:30:14.000
made with, for example, the election of Barack Obama as president?

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:22.000
I don't know that I would ever say that something is inevitable.

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:26.000
I would say that it is sadly not surprising.

00:30:26.000 --> 00:30:30.000
I mean, I think this is one of the things that we have talked about.

00:30:31.000 --> 00:30:38.000
And I've talked with members of Congress, with community leaders across the country.

00:30:39.000 --> 00:30:47.000
It was almost, we were all, of course, horrified by what happened on January 6.

00:30:47.000 --> 00:30:50.000
It was something that no one would see happen to our country.

00:30:50.000 --> 00:30:53.000
But I think what's important to note is that it wasn't surprising.

00:30:53.000 --> 00:30:59.000
It wasn't surprising for communities, for Black, brown, Arab, Muslim, Jewish,

00:30:59.000 --> 00:31:01.000
Sikhs, disabled, LGBTQ communities.

00:31:01.000 --> 00:31:02.000
We were not surprised.

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:03.000
So they answered your question.

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:12.000
And I think we can both be horrified and not surprised and know that yes, we have seen this before.

00:31:13.000 --> 00:31:20.000
But I think what we believe, and I think following the leadership of Black and brown leaders

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:27.000
across the country's history, is that the power to change this, as reside in communities,

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:34.000
and that we have, we are at a time now where, yes, we are glad that most people are paying attention

00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:39.000
to it. It is somewhat painful, but it took what, you know, what happened on January 6,

00:31:39.000 --> 00:31:42.000
for people to pay attention to something that's been a daily lived reality.

00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:46.000
The communities of color in this country for generations.

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:53.000
But now that we have this focus, we are determined to make sure that we are actually able to use

00:31:53.000 --> 00:31:57.000
that focus in the way that actually makes a real difference. It changes policies.

00:31:57.000 --> 00:32:02.000
It starts to see the kinds of systemic reform and systemic changes that will actually

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:09.000
make them stay different for the next generation. Because I think, you know, I have to say,

00:32:10.000 --> 00:32:18.000
here's so much pain. I've done this work for almost two decades about hate incidents and

00:32:18.000 --> 00:32:24.000
hate crimes. I think there is always such a deep pain, but also a such deep determination to

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:29.000
fight back. I think I hear that same thing now. But I also think we need to recognize that it's

00:32:29.000 --> 00:32:35.000
somewhat painful, especially when white people sort of act surprised about what happened on

00:32:35.000 --> 00:32:43.000
January 6. I think there is a recognition that perhaps there is a new, there is a growing awareness

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:48.000
and that is a positive thing, but it's somewhat painful that people with the privilege to look the

00:32:48.000 --> 00:32:55.000
other way has been doing that for too long. You've been involved in helping communities fight against

00:32:55.000 --> 00:33:02.000
hate crimes and the expressions of hate. What do you know? What have we learned about what works best?

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:09.000
I think we've learned a few things. I think the most core and central thing is that what

00:33:09.000 --> 00:33:14.000
works best is when you actually listen to the people who are targeted for hate. There are often

00:33:14.000 --> 00:33:19.000
many well-intentioned people who are not part of the communities that have ideas about what will work

00:33:19.000 --> 00:33:24.000
and what people want, but the reality is we need to listen and what does that mean? That means

00:33:24.000 --> 00:33:31.000
recognizing that what public faith you look like and does not mean more law enforcement. It means

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:38.000
investment in communities. It means, you know, if you actually look at what's most effective, it means

00:33:39.000 --> 00:33:42.000
going to the organizations that have earned the trust of people who are targeted for hate.

00:33:43.000 --> 00:33:49.000
It means going to NAACP branches, local LGBT centers, mosques, synagogues,

00:33:51.000 --> 00:33:55.000
local organizations that support people with disabilities. It is talking to the people who

00:33:55.000 --> 00:34:00.000
actually represent and serve the people who are targeted and asking them what are the kinds of

00:34:00.000 --> 00:34:03.000
things that would work. It makes sure that they are at the table. So if you look at things like

00:34:03.000 --> 00:34:09.000
hate crime data, we know it under-reported. The Department of Justice itself knows that. The same

00:34:09.000 --> 00:34:13.000
Department of Justice that reports the FBI data as around 7,000 hate crimes occurring in the

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:20.000
country across the country. Every year, that's the Department of Justice that says actually,

00:34:20.000 --> 00:34:24.000
if we use the sampling system that is a more accurate number, it's closer to 200,000.

00:34:25.000 --> 00:34:28.000
So what does that say to a community? If you are living in a jurisdiction where the law

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:33.000
enforcement agency or your state, sometimes entire states are reporting that no hate crimes occur

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:38.000
here. That tells the community sort of who is being protected, who matters, who doesn't.

00:34:38.000 --> 00:34:43.000
And so when we talk about data, it's one of those things where when you actually listen to

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:53.000
communities, it is very hard to describe the pain that comes from being targeted for hate violence

00:34:53.000 --> 00:34:59.000
because of who you are. But when you double that pain by not even counting it, by not acknowledging

00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:06.000
what happened yet again, appearing to try and cover up with the nature of the threat, the harm,

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:13.000
that's deeply damaging as well. There is a conversation that precedes your involvement.

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:21.000
You might be surprised. The cliche was, we should have a cop on every corner. And I wonder now

00:35:21.000 --> 00:35:30.000
in the face of the revelations that there's so many white nationalist haters in essence

00:35:30.000 --> 00:35:40.000
in law enforcement, if that was part of the, if that is what that meant, that we need to have a

00:35:40.000 --> 00:35:48.000
slave catcher or somebody an overseer in every neighborhood to make sure that the people not

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:52.000
obey the law, but rather that they just stay in their place.

00:35:54.000 --> 00:36:03.000
I should say I hope I am very aware of how, and like I mentioned, this fight against

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:08.000
hate has been happening before our country started. So I am very aware in the big scene of things

00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:13.000
I have played, I have been fortunate to work alongside people for a very short period of time.

00:36:14.000 --> 00:36:19.000
But I absolutely, I absolutely know that history in your ass is what we write, and that is why,

00:36:19.000 --> 00:36:25.000
again, when we talk about what works, if you talk to communities, again, the communities who are

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:29.000
targeted for hate, they are not saying that more law enforcement will be helpful in fact,

00:36:29.000 --> 00:36:35.000
they are saying the opposite. And I think in some ways, if you talk to some law enforcement

00:36:35.000 --> 00:36:38.000
leaders, they also recommend that. They shouldn't be responding to all of the incentives

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:42.000
they were responding to, and that's, that there's a big push to sort of try to address that. So

00:36:43.000 --> 00:36:47.000
I think, you know, I think for too long, there has been a sense that,

00:36:49.000 --> 00:36:55.000
you know, the public safety has been erroneously equated with more police, and that is not,

00:36:57.000 --> 00:37:00.000
that's just, if people have been listening to the community, that is not, that is not,

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:04.000
that's not what public safety means. So I think you're,

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:12.000
absolutely right in pointing out that, that is, that continues to be a problem, and

00:37:12.000 --> 00:37:16.000
the people are creating that. Again, you just look at January 6th, you see the number of people

00:37:16.000 --> 00:37:21.000
who either had kind or form or affiliations in military or law enforcement to see the problem.

00:37:22.000 --> 00:37:27.000
But again, if you talk to communities, in the aftermath of an officer, when officer kills someone,

00:37:28.000 --> 00:37:34.000
every time they talk to the community, they will identify someone in that agency who had a known

00:37:34.000 --> 00:37:39.000
affiliation. And so I think, yes, I think your point is, is very well taken, and that I think that's

00:37:40.000 --> 00:37:46.000
absolutely, again, that's partly why we're at this point now, is because people have been

00:37:46.000 --> 00:37:51.000
pointing that out for generations, and the fact that people have been ignoring it is not acceptable,

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:54.000
but now we're at a point that should act on it.

00:37:56.000 --> 00:38:05.000
The last several months have really pointed out the disparity, the contradiction in the approach

00:38:06.000 --> 00:38:14.000
to nonviolent black protesters beat up and and and really threatened by police, pushed around by

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:23.000
police, whereas the January 6th violent protesters, well, they were eventually contained forcefully,

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:29.000
but they weren't beat up and arrested and thrown in in jails the way people used to be done at

00:38:29.000 --> 00:38:36.000
civil demonstrations. That's right. So does that indicate the presence of

00:38:37.000 --> 00:38:43.000
something troubling in the upper echelons above the command level of law enforcement?

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:49.000
It's absolutely, I mean, it speaks again to what, you know, I think kind of what you started

00:38:49.000 --> 00:38:54.000
with conversation with, because we're talking about systemic racism. We're not talking about it

00:38:54.000 --> 00:39:00.000
in some sort of like academic way. We are talking about it in a way that deeply affects

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:08.000
in harmed people. So the fact that the response to armed white nationalist insurrectionists

00:39:09.000 --> 00:39:15.000
was the response that we saw, the initial response that we saw. When you compare that with the

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:24.000
response to peaceful protesters demanding racial justice across the country, without questions,

00:39:24.000 --> 00:39:31.000
that speaks to a deeper and a larger problem. But I think that again, people have color

00:39:31.000 --> 00:39:37.000
has been demanding action on for generations. And so I hope that, you know, I do think that

00:39:37.000 --> 00:39:46.000
that contrast, they shouldn't be compared. People protesting peacefully for racial justice or civil

00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:52.000
rights. There's just no comparison to white national insurrectionists trying to overtake the

00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:57.000
government. And yet the responses were so disparate that it was important that we look at those

00:39:57.000 --> 00:40:04.000
and acknowledge those, the tools are there. Congress created statutes that could be used right now.

00:40:04.000 --> 00:40:11.000
There are over 50 statutes that could be applied to domestic terrorism crimes. There are hate crimes

00:40:11.000 --> 00:40:16.000
statutes. There are conspiracy statutes. The fact that they haven't been used against white nationalists

00:40:16.000 --> 00:40:22.000
is not a question of not having the tools, but the question of not having the will. We've often

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:27.000
worked with our colleagues, the national action network. And just to give you kind of one quick

00:40:27.000 --> 00:40:32.000
comparison, if you look at what the national action network had to do in order to have it incredibly

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:38.000
expected and peaceful march on Washington over the summer, the steps they went through, the money they

00:40:38.000 --> 00:40:45.000
had to invest. It's a kind of, you know, the multiple steps they took to make sure that people were

00:40:45.000 --> 00:40:51.000
safe and coded, that they took all of these actions. They did every single thing. And they had

00:40:51.000 --> 00:40:57.000
an incredibly effective and peaceful protest. When you think about the steps they had to take,

00:40:57.000 --> 00:41:01.000
compared to what happened when violent white nationalists owned the Capitol, it is,

00:41:02.000 --> 00:41:06.000
it is hard not to make those comparisons. I just, my only caution is that we shouldn't be comparing

00:41:06.000 --> 00:41:12.000
peaceful protest or racial justice with white national concerns. Beckerman Roam, Director of the

00:41:12.000 --> 00:41:17.000
Fighting, Hate and Bias at the Leadership Conference. Thank you. Thank you for talking with us.

00:41:18.000 --> 00:41:19.000
Thank you so much.

