00:43:11.000 --> 00:43:19.000
Sarah Anderson, Global Economy Project Director and Inequality.org co-editor at the Institute for

00:43:19.000 --> 00:43:27.000
Policy Studies, testified at the hearing and explained to me how CEO Pay has exploded over the

00:43:27.000 --> 00:43:35.000
decades. a primary cause of the explosion of executive compensation over the past decades is the

00:43:35.000 --> 00:43:43.000
shift from cash salary, like most of us get to these very complex packages that include

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:49.000
different kinds of stock based pay. The argument for that was that this would more tightly align

00:43:49.000 --> 00:43:55.000
the interests of the CEO with the shareholders and ensure a pay for performance system because

00:43:55.000 --> 00:44:01.000
they would only get these big payouts if their stock price went up. Instead, it's in mind,

00:44:01.000 --> 00:44:07.000
been a real disaster, not just because it has resulted in these gargantuan pay packages,

00:44:07.000 --> 00:44:14.000
but it's encouraged executives to think in a very short-term way. So, okay, what can I do to bump

00:44:14.000 --> 00:44:20.000
up my stock price so I can hit my bonus targets for the year? Well, let's see, I can slash jobs,

00:44:20.000 --> 00:44:27.000
I can cut investment in research and development, I can dump a bunch of toxic in the river,

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:35.000
very harmful things for society that might inflate their stock price and his personal paycheck in

00:44:35.000 --> 00:44:42.000
the short term, but are bad for the rest of us in the long term. Sure. You cite a Harvard study that

00:44:42.000 --> 00:44:49.000
found economic harm of excessive executive pay in the form of higher employee turnover and lower

00:44:49.000 --> 00:44:56.000
sales. I wonder, can you talk about why excessive pay causes these economic harms? And is it possible

00:44:56.000 --> 00:45:02.000
to quantify on the flip side the economic benefits of limiting executive pay? Well, there have

00:45:02.000 --> 00:45:07.000
been a lot of studies over the decades and I was really pleased I found that study by current

00:45:07.000 --> 00:45:13.000
Treasury Secretary Janet Yellen, it's actually from 1990, so it was even before the really big

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:21.000
explosion in the gaps between CEO and worker pay, but she put forward a theory and backs it up

00:45:21.000 --> 00:45:27.000
in this paper that workers are going to work less hard if they feel like they're not fairly rewarded.

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:32.000
And if the guy in the corner office is making hundreds, if not a thousand times more than you,

00:45:32.000 --> 00:45:38.000
you're more likely to feel like your contribution to the company is just not being rewarded in

00:45:38.000 --> 00:45:45.000
in a fair way. And so she said it was both like supported by research, but also just common sense.

00:45:45.000 --> 00:45:50.000
And since then there have been a lot of other studies that look at it and you know, I was involved

00:45:50.000 --> 00:45:56.000
in a fight over attacks on companies with big CEO pay in Portland, Oregon and it was actually the

00:45:56.000 --> 00:46:04.000
mayor at the time had worked for a big cooperatively owned engineering company. And he decided to vote

00:46:04.000 --> 00:46:09.000
for the tax because he saw it as a pro business tax because in his experience at a cooperatively

00:46:09.000 --> 00:46:15.000
owned company with a really narrow gap, he felt like he'd seen firsthand how that had really brought

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:19.000
out the best in his colleagues. They were a very profitable company that did much better than

00:46:19.000 --> 00:46:27.000
their competitors who had the traditional very hierarchical structure and pay system. So I think both,

00:46:27.000 --> 00:46:33.000
you know, like Layton and Yellen said common sense and a lot of business glue and other kinds of

00:46:33.000 --> 00:46:40.000
research over the years have indicated that extreme gaps are not good for employ morale. And if

00:46:40.000 --> 00:46:46.000
you have bad morale, it tends to turn into lower productivity and higher turnover rates.

00:46:47.000 --> 00:46:54.000
To move to particular policy solutions, as your testimony made clear, the tax excessive CEO pay

00:46:54.000 --> 00:46:59.000
act that was recently introduced isn't a hard cap on pay, but rather as the name suggests, the tax

00:46:59.000 --> 00:47:05.000
disincentive to overpay executives. And because it's a graduated or progressive tax, I'd imagine

00:47:05.000 --> 00:47:10.000
that firms might respond to it differently depending on their context. And so do you have a sense of

00:47:11.000 --> 00:47:15.000
how firms might respond generally speaking given that it's a graduated tax and accordingly

00:47:15.000 --> 00:47:22.000
how much this bill could reduce pay disparities on average? All very good questions. So the way

00:47:22.000 --> 00:47:28.000
the tax would work is the wider your pay gap, the higher your federal corporate tax rate.

00:47:28.000 --> 00:47:34.000
And the tax increases kick in for companies that have to CEO pay 50 times more than median worker

00:47:34.000 --> 00:47:39.000
pay. So below that, any companies with gaps of less than 50 to one, they wouldn't pay another

00:47:39.000 --> 00:47:47.000
dime. And then like you said, it's graduated ending with the ratios of 500 and more. For them,

00:47:47.000 --> 00:47:55.000
their corporate tax rate would increase by 5 percentage points. So from 21 to 26%. How companies

00:47:55.000 --> 00:48:03.000
will respond? We honestly don't know. But I think either way we win because what we would like

00:48:03.000 --> 00:48:10.000
to see is companies responding by narrowing their pay gaps, both by bringing down the top end

00:48:10.000 --> 00:48:16.000
and lifting up worker wages. If they refuse to do that, then they'll pay more taxes. And we can

00:48:16.000 --> 00:48:21.000
use that revenue for something that that might reduce inequality. And one thing I like to compare

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:29.000
it to is like cigarette taxes. So they were designed to influence behavior to try to reduce

00:48:29.000 --> 00:48:34.000
smoking rates. And they haven't eliminated smoking entirely, but they have contributed to a

00:48:34.000 --> 00:48:40.000
reduction of smoking rates. And in the meantime, they've generated a lot of revenue that's gone

00:48:40.000 --> 00:48:46.000
into health programs. So I think this is a similar thing. I see the extreme gaps between CEO and

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:53.000
worker pay as a problem for broader society in the same way that smoking contributes to increased

00:48:53.000 --> 00:49:01.000
health care costs and all of that. And this is a tax that wouldn't mandate a certain cap on CEO

00:49:01.000 --> 00:49:07.000
pay, but it would give them an economic incentive to rein things in. You mentioned seven other policy

00:49:07.000 --> 00:49:13.000
solutions to excessive executive pay and your testimony, including a financial transaction tax,

00:49:13.000 --> 00:49:19.000
closing various tax loopholes, enforcing some Dodd-Frank provisions, etc. Is there some ideal mix

00:49:19.000 --> 00:49:25.000
of these proposals to limit excessive pay or is the most obvious solution of a hard cap the best

00:49:25.000 --> 00:49:33.000
solution? Yeah, I think we need a full tool box. I think a lot of these proposals that I list go at

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:39.000
sort of a little bit different issues. The financial transaction tax is a tax on each trade,

00:49:39.000 --> 00:49:47.000
Wall Street trade. So it would most affect the people engaged in the stock flipping every second

00:49:47.000 --> 00:49:52.000
kind of crazy Wall Street casino behavior that doesn't do anything for the rest of the economy,

00:49:52.000 --> 00:49:59.000
but it's been extremely lucrative and so has inflated Wall Street executive bonuses. So that's

00:49:59.000 --> 00:50:04.000
a little bit different of an issue than the pay ratio problem that I've been talking about.

00:50:04.000 --> 00:50:12.000
Yeah, so I would go for more of a mix. I will say though that back in like the post-World War II era,

00:50:12.000 --> 00:50:20.000
when they had very high taxes on individual income, you know, as much as 90% under the Eisenhower era,

00:50:20.000 --> 00:50:27.000
CEO pay wasn't as high, and I think that's logical because why pay this guy all this money if it's

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:33.000
just mostly going to be taxed away anyway. So I will say that if we could raise the top

00:50:33.000 --> 00:50:40.000
marginal income tax for just for individual income, that would go a long way towards handling the

00:50:40.000 --> 00:50:48.000
CEO pay problem as well. But I like the pay ratio tax idea because it isn't incentive to both

00:50:48.000 --> 00:50:54.000
bring down the top and lift up the bottom, and it falls on the corporations that have been most

00:50:54.000 --> 00:51:00.000
contributing to inequality. So yeah, I think we need to try different approaches. And I also think

00:51:00.000 --> 00:51:08.000
that this, anything when you when you add the CEO pay issue to a tax idea, it broadens the appeal

00:51:08.000 --> 00:51:15.000
because the public across the political spectrum is outraged about excessive CEO pay in a way that,

00:51:15.000 --> 00:51:20.000
you know, has just been off the charts for a long time. But lots of people don't think there's

00:51:20.000 --> 00:51:24.000
much we can do about it, but here is a practical approach to addressing that.

00:51:25.000 --> 00:51:29.000
You make the point in your in your testimony that a lot of the country's billionaires made their

00:51:29.000 --> 00:51:36.000
fortunes as being CEOs. And so I'd imagine in the long run a limit to excessive CEO pay might

00:51:36.000 --> 00:51:40.000
help mitigate wealth inequality in addition to income inequality. But I'd also imagine wealth

00:51:40.000 --> 00:51:45.000
inequality deserves its own policy proposals. And before I ask about particular policy,

00:51:45.000 --> 00:51:51.000
I wonder is there, do you have the sense that there's more of a political appetite to address

00:51:51.000 --> 00:51:58.000
income inequality versus, or rather than wealth inequality, both inside DC and outside the beltway?

00:51:59.000 --> 00:52:05.000
I think a huge issue is that people don't know the difference between income and wealth. And so we,

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:10.000
we have recognized that by inner publications, always really trying to spell it out.

00:52:11.000 --> 00:52:16.000
Because people think you were talking about income when you're talking about wealth. And wealth

00:52:16.000 --> 00:52:23.000
is what you've accumulated. It's the value of all of your property and your investment holdings and,

00:52:23.000 --> 00:52:29.000
you know, and so forth. Whereas income is what you earn every year. And so I think the American

00:52:29.000 --> 00:52:35.000
public has a lot to learn about that. And I think since many people don't know the difference,

00:52:35.000 --> 00:52:41.000
many people don't get how the wealth gaps are even bigger than the income gaps. And that's because

00:52:41.000 --> 00:52:47.000
of generation after generation families accumulating this money oftentimes, you know, when you're

00:52:47.000 --> 00:52:53.000
looking at the Wal-Mart, the Walton family that owns Wal-Mart and the Mars family that owns

00:52:53.000 --> 00:52:58.000
Candy Company. And those kind of families, you're really looking at intergenerational wealth

00:52:58.000 --> 00:53:07.000
accumulation. That's just, you know, beyond people's wildest imagination. And so, yeah, a tax on

00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:14.000
CEO pay couldn't address the wealth problem totally because it has accumulated over so many years.

00:53:14.000 --> 00:53:20.000
It can help prevent further accumulation in the future. But that's why I think we need a wealth

00:53:20.000 --> 00:53:27.000
tax as well as taxes on annual income. And it seems like this wealth tax proposed by Senators

00:53:27.000 --> 00:53:32.000
Warren and Sanders is the most direct way to address wealth inequality that's currently on the

00:53:32.000 --> 00:53:37.000
table. But it seems like in some ways, administration of that tax could be more difficult than the

00:53:37.000 --> 00:53:43.000
administration of an income tax or of the CEO tax that we were discussing. Can you talk about some

00:53:43.000 --> 00:53:49.000
of these difficulties, particularly the problems in accurately assessing a person's wealth and

00:53:49.000 --> 00:53:55.000
the potential tax evasion problem as well? Yeah, I mean, there's a whole industry of people who's

00:53:55.000 --> 00:54:00.000
job it is is to help wealthy people hide their wealth. And so that is going to be an issue. I don't

00:54:00.000 --> 00:54:07.000
think it's a reason to not try to do it because there's also tons of evasion of income taxes,

00:54:07.000 --> 00:54:12.000
you know, hiding it overseas and whatnot. But nobody says, oh, well, it's not having income

00:54:12.000 --> 00:54:20.000
tax anymore because we don't have 100% enforcement of that either. So I really applaud them for moving

00:54:20.000 --> 00:54:25.000
ahead. I also want to add that another way to deal with wealth concentration is the estate tax.

00:54:25.000 --> 00:54:30.000
And boy, is there ever polarization in that? There's just a bunch of Republicans that called for it

00:54:30.000 --> 00:54:37.000
to be at 100% repealed. And then Senators, Sanders and others are calling for a stronger estate tax

00:54:37.000 --> 00:54:44.000
with more graduated rates. So they're super polarized around that. But, you know, one reason why I do

00:54:44.000 --> 00:54:51.000
have hope that a lot of these spare tax ideas could have a chance this year in a way that they

00:54:51.000 --> 00:54:57.000
haven't had for a long, long time is because there is going to be a big infrastructure package

00:54:57.000 --> 00:55:03.000
coming together to help with economic recovery from the COVID crisis. And hopefully it'll have all

00:55:03.000 --> 00:55:09.000
kinds of exciting things about green infrastructure and, you know, job creation and in ways that really

00:55:09.000 --> 00:55:15.000
strengthen our economy for the long term. But even among Democrats, they're going to be worried

00:55:15.000 --> 00:55:21.000
about the size of the spending that the dollar amount attached to that recovery. And so they're going

00:55:21.000 --> 00:55:27.000
to want to pay for most of it through new revenue sources. So there's going to be huge pressure,

00:55:27.000 --> 00:55:32.000
like Senators mentioned, and cinema have both said they're worried about the deficit. They would

00:55:32.000 --> 00:55:39.000
support a big package if it had pay force, you know, new tax ideas. At the Institute of Policy

00:55:39.000 --> 00:55:43.000
Studies, we also point out like, hey, you can cut a lot from the military budget and, you know,

00:55:44.000 --> 00:55:49.000
reduce the deficit that way. It must be mentioned, it's not mentioned enough in Washington, I think. But

00:55:51.000 --> 00:55:57.000
so I think there's a real chance that ideas like the wealth tax, tax success of CEO pay,

00:55:57.000 --> 00:56:02.000
stronger state tax, increased income and corporate tax rates and these kind of financial transaction

00:56:02.000 --> 00:56:08.000
tax, I'll mention that again. They have a real shot because of that dynamic, because people know

00:56:08.000 --> 00:56:14.000
they want to really get the economy humming again. And to do that, we need a lot of public investment.

00:56:14.000 --> 00:56:17.000
And there's going to be a big question about how to pay for it.

00:56:18.000 --> 00:56:25.000
That's Sarah Anderson, global economy project director and inequality.org co-editor at the

00:56:25.000 --> 00:56:37.000
Institute for Policy Studies. For Monday morning QB, I'm Chris Banger-Grounds.

00:56:37.000 --> 00:57:01.000
As this women's history month draws to an end, we honor phenomenal women, phenomenal women like

00:57:01.000 --> 00:57:06.000
Deb Hollen, who became the first indigenous person to head the department of the interior.

00:57:07.000 --> 00:57:12.000
We honor representative Park Cannon for her bravery in fighting for voting rights in Georgia.

00:57:13.000 --> 00:57:21.000
We honor Amanda Nguyen, whose viral video about anti-Asian violence started a national conversation.

00:57:22.000 --> 00:57:29.000
We honor Dr. Rachel Levine, who is now the first openly transgender official to be confirmed by

00:57:29.000 --> 00:57:36.000
the U.S. Senate. We honor Jelissa Renoso, who is now the co-chair of the Gender Policy Council.

00:57:37.000 --> 00:57:43.000
All of these women and more, we honor you for your courage, your vulnerability, your freedom,

00:57:43.000 --> 00:57:50.000
your intellect, your joy and your strength. This is phenomenal woman by Maya Angelou.

00:57:50.000 --> 00:58:01.000
Phenomenal woman. Many people wonder where my secret lies. I'm not cute or built to suit a fashion model

00:58:01.000 --> 00:58:09.000
size. When I start to tell them, they think I'm telling lies. I say, it's in the reach of my arms,

00:58:09.000 --> 00:58:17.000
the span of my hips, the stride of my step, the curl of my lips. I'm a woman, phenomenally.

00:58:18.000 --> 00:58:26.000
I walk into a room just as cool as you please, and to amend the fellow stand, or fall down on their

00:58:26.000 --> 00:58:35.000
knees. Then they swarm around me, a hive of honey bees. I say, it's the fire in my eyes,

00:58:35.000 --> 00:58:45.000
the flash of my teeth, the swing in my waist, the joy in my feet. I'm a woman phenomenally.

00:58:45.000 --> 00:58:52.000
Men themselves have wondered what they see in me. They try so much, but they can't touch my inner

00:58:52.000 --> 00:59:00.000
mystery. When I try to show them, they say they still can't see. I say, it's in the arch of my back,

00:59:00.000 --> 00:59:10.000
the sun of my smile, the ride of my breasts, the grace of my style. I'm a woman phenomenally.

00:59:11.000 --> 00:59:19.000
Now you understand just why my head's not bowed. I don't shout, or jump about, or have to talk

00:59:19.000 --> 00:59:27.000
real loud. When you see me passing, it ought to make you proud. I say, it's in the click of my

00:59:27.000 --> 00:59:37.000
heels, the bend of my hair, the palms of my hands, the need for my care, because I'm a woman.

00:59:37.000 --> 00:59:45.000
Phenomenally, phenomenal woman, that's my mother and all your mothers and my grandmothers

00:59:45.000 --> 00:59:52.000
and your grandmothers and my great-grandmothers and your greats and my great-greats and all you women

00:59:53.000 --> 00:59:54.000
and me.

01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:06.000
And that's our show for today. Monday morning QB is produced by Chris Manger Drowns

01:00:07.000 --> 01:00:07.000
Mara Evering.

